                "name": "Conor Fogarty",
                "href": "/profile/Conor-Fogarty-3"
            },
            "answer_text": "I wouldn\u2019t say frowned upon, although it is not nearly as common as a century ago. In fact, geisha houses in this day and age are few and the services of geishas exclusive and pricey. It is one of many aspects of Japanese entertainment culture that has endured over the centuries, even if it is practiced a lot less today. If I may venture as to why you might be asking if geishas are frowned upon in Japan, perhaps you\u2019re referring to its connection to prostitution? It cannot be stressed enough that geisha and prostitution are distinct in that one is a uniquely-Japanese social activity and the other an industry involving the selling of sex. Admittedly, the lines can be blurred, and they were, but the distinction lies in the difference between which of the two is limited to affectionate companionship. Geishas are entertainers, musicians, conversationalists, painters, and dancers. Anything beyond that is a matter of voluntary discretion or, in some tragic historical cases, coercion. Today, actual geishas are defined by their inclusion in celebrations and special events, typically for wealthy businessmen or politicians. These women are trained, often since before adolescence, how to talk amicably and entertain their guests with a variety of talents. Their job is to make their clients feel comfortable as they enjoy their new appointment or position. In the West, this could be compared to escort services, although it is far less transactional and usually less client-specific. Moreover, there may be a price point at which an escort may be willing to solicit sex, whereas it will likely be out of the question as a matter of custom for geishas. Is it still the case that a geisha could become the mistress of an affluent Japanese man? Yes, as it would seem that members of the elite class still hold an affinity for geisha mistresses. Regardless, a significantly greater number of Japanese are entering business and politics instead of relying on the customer service industry and historical lifestyles such as geisha. ",
