            "author_info": {
                "name": "Hazel Sarah Federico",
                "href": "/profile/Hazel-Sarah-Federico"
            },
            "answer_text": "No, geishas are not frowned upon. I think the fascination about geishas became stronger when Arthur Golden\u2019s bestselling book, Memoirs of a Geisha, came out. I loved reading that book. I read it several times and learned a bunch of things about geisha. So when I came to Japan five years ago, I had a particular image of geishas in my mind. However, as I would soon find out, they\u2019re quite rare nowadays. It\u2019s a fast disappearing industry. Most people visit Kyoto, to get a rare glimpse of a geisha (what they\u2019re normally called in Tokyo or in general), or geiko (as they\u2019re commonly called in Kyoto). I have a friend who visits Kyoto several times a year and have paid for the services of a geiko. They said they would sing some songs and play some games. From what I heard, it\u2019s the rich people or big businesses who can afford to hire the services of a full-fledged geiko. As explained in the Golden\u2019s book, people\u2019s perception of geishas, even back then, was quite different from how they viewed prostitutes. Geishas were respected for their knowledge of the arts and for how well they behave. Back then, they made rounds on tea houses and their income would depend on the number of teahouses they visited and how many incense sticks have been burned (one stick corresponds to one hour). There were practices that others might deem questionable like the mizuage, essentially the auction of a young geisha\u2019s virginity, and also the fact that for some of them, the main goal is to find a husband or sponsor, and it didn\u2019t matter if he was married or not. I\u2019m not sure whether these practices still exist today but in general, geishas don\u2019t have a bad image in Japan. ",
