            "author_info": {
                "name": "David W. Rudlin",
                "href": "/profile/David-W-Rudlin"
            },
            "answer_text": "Not at all! There just aren\u2019t many of them. In Asakusa, the geisha capital of Tokyo, there are less than 30 of them left. And the average age is well over 60. Despite what you see in western movies, geisha aren\u2019t prostitutes. The name itself translates as \u201cartist\u201d, and it is very, very hard work. Which is why there are so few of them left. One friend of mine began training at the age of 6. Hours and hours of instruction in comportment, traditional Japanese dance, traditional Japanese instruments, wordplay, etc. etc. etc. All of that has to be paid for, as do all the kimono that start at $10,000 and skyrocket from there. Each story is different, but in general a geisha is unlikely to break even until her late 20\u2019s. That\u2019s a deal very few modern Japanese are willing to take. Another problem is customers. The days when Japanese executives had massive entertainment budgets are long gone, and when an evening with a geisha adds $10,000 to a dinner bill that often runs $1,000/head, there aren\u2019t many people willing to foot the bill personally. Moreover the customer has a role to play in a geisha performance, and if you don\u2019t know your lines, the evening can be truly dull. While I\u2019m not a fan of geisha at work (because I can\u2019t fully appreciate their skill), privately they\u2019re pretty amazing. Very witty. Very quick. Graceful. Elegant. Drink like sailors on shore leave. It\u2019s actually very sad watching them go. ",
